# Architecture Boundaries

## Allowed dependency direction

```
UI → API → CommandBus → Orchestrators → Compute Kernels → Storage / Provenance
```

- **UI** may call **API**.
- **API routes must remain thin.** They may validate transport-level input and call application services.
- **API routes must not contain scientific computation.**
- **API routes must not directly call compute kernels.**
- **API routes must not write artifacts or provenance directly.**
- **API routes must go through CommandBus/application services for experiment-producing actions.**
- **Application services** may call **orchestrators**.
- **Orchestrators** may call **compute ports**, **validators**, **repositories**, **artifact store**, and **provenance ledger**.
- **Compute kernels** must be deterministic and isolated. They receive parameters and return results. No side effects, no imports from upper layers.
- **Agents** may only read approved context and write labeled suggestions or explanations. They never sit on the main data path.

## Forbidden dependencies

- **Compute must not import API.** Kernels are pure; they know nothing about HTTP or routing.
- **Compute must not import agents.** Scientific computation must not depend on AI assistance.
- **Compute must not import storage adapters.** Data flows through ports, not direct database access.
- **Frontend must not import backend modules.** Communication happens only via the API boundary.
- **Agents are runtime side-channel assistants only when explicitly added later.** Development coding agents are not runtime scientific agents.
- **Runtime agents may create AgentOutput or SuggestedCommand records only when such schemas exist.**
- **Runtime agents must not execute commands, mutate runs, overwrite artifacts, edit provenance, or modify code.**

## Immutability rule

Finished runs are immutable. No process — human, automated, or agent — may silently alter a completed run's parameters, artifacts, metrics, or provenance.

## Provenance rule

Every experiment-producing feature must emit provenance records. Every artifact must carry a content hash.
